  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and around me. Growing up in a working-class family in Milan, where my parents had limited education, I often felt that my ability to understand complex subjects like math or physics was somehow tied to my background. When I was a teenager, I'd sit with friends who were studying engineering, and they'd mention how they felt nervous during exams because they'd heard that 'girls aren't good at math' or 'people from my neighborhood don't do well in science.' It's a real thing, and it's not just about gender or race—it's about the fear that your group's stereotypes might affect your performance. I've seen this in my own work as a delivery driver too; sometimes people assume I'm not 'smart enough' for technical roles because I don't have a college degree. That kind of self-doubt can really hold people back. The question is, should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. Instead of focusing on fixing individual students, we need to change how we talk about STEM in communities like mine. For example, if a local school in Milan starts a program that shows kids from my background succeeding in tech fields, it could help break down those stereotypes. It's not about making everyone the same—it's about creating spaces where people feel they belong. And for me, as someone who's been through it, it's about recognizing that everyone deserves a chance to do their best, no matter where they come from.",
